thanks for the hints.
After debuggen some hours in this area we found some more:

1. I am not an expert of plugin class loading, but in my limited knowledge the situation may be the following:
Usually a plugin hides the jars it uses itself.
Our own plugin is doing this with the log4j.jar.
So other plugins will not see the log4j.jar if they are programmed well.
However the Birt-Viewer plugin bypasses this plugin encapsulation.
Our problem occurs in class org.eclipse.birt.report.viewer.utilities.ViewerClassLoaderWrapper
there the log4j classes are loaded via the following code:

public Class loadClass( String className ) throws ClassNotFoundException
{
	try
	{
		return bundle.loadClass( className );
	}
	catch(ClassNotFoundException e)
	{

		for ( Iterator it = othersBundles.iterator( ); it.hasNext( ); )
		{
			try
			{
				String name = (String) it.next( );
				Bundle b = findBundle(name);
				if (b != null)
				{
					return b.loadClass(className);
				}
			}
			catch(ClassNotFoundException ee)
			{

			}
			}
	}
	throw new ClassNotFoundException("class not fond name is " + className);
}

This method direct calls the bundle classloaders. I am certainly not an expert in this case, but to me this seems to be the root cause of the problems. Please correct me if I am wrong.

2. The commons-logging-api.jar is part of the release commons-logging 1.0.3.
I could solve our problem when patching this jar. The patched version
returns false in method isLog4JAvailable()  of class org.apache.commons.logging.impl.LogFactoryImpl:

   protected boolean isLog4JAvailable() {
	return false;
   }

So log4j is not used by the tomcat plugin.
I can keep the batik and hibernate plugins and leave our own plugin as it is.
This is certainly a hack.
